CS 320 Portfolio Reflection

This repository includes selected work from my software testing, automation, and quality assurance course. From Project One, I included my Contact Service files: Contact.java, ContactService.java, 
ContactTest.java, and ContactServiceTest.java. From Project Two, I included my summary and reflections report. Together, these files show my ability to create Java classes based on requirements, 
write JUnit tests, validate inputs, and reflect on software testing strategies.

How can I ensure that my code, program, or software is functional and secure?

I can ensure that my code is functional and secure by writing tests that prove the program behaves correctly with both valid and invalid input. 
In this project, I used JUnit tests to confirm that contact objects could be created, updated, retrieved, and deleted correctly. 
I also tested invalid inputs, such as null values, phone numbers that were not exactly ten digits, and contact IDs that were longer than allowed. 
This helped ensure that the program rejected bad data instead of allowing it into the system.

Security also starts with controlling what data is accepted by the program. For example, my Contact class validates fields before assigning values, 
and my ContactService class prevents duplicate contact IDs. These checks help protect data integrity. 
In future projects, I would continue improving security by validating inputs, limiting access to sensitive operations, avoiding unnecessary data exposure, 
and testing for failure cases instead of only testing successful paths.

How do I interpret user needs and incorporate them into a program?

I interpret user needs by breaking requirements down into specific behaviors the software must support. 
For this project, the requirements stated that each contact needed a unique ID, a first name, a last name, a phone number, and an address, with specific limits for each field. 
I translated those needs into class attributes, validation rules, service methods, and unit tests.

Instead of guessing what the program should do, I used the requirements as a checklist. 
If the requirement said the contact ID could not be longer than ten characters, I wrote code to enforce that rule and a test to verify it. 
This approach helped me connect the customer’s needs directly to the final implementation. It also made the program easier to test because each requirement had a clear expected result.

How do I approach designing software?

I approach software design by first identifying the main objects, responsibilities, and rules in the system. 
For the Contact Service, I separated the contact data from the service that manages contacts. 
The Contact class is responsible for storing and validating individual contact information, while the ContactService class is responsible for adding, deleting, updating, and retrieving contacts.

This separation made the design easier to understand and test. Each class had a clear purpose, which reduced confusion and made the code easier to maintain. 
  Going forward, I plan to continue designing software in small, focused pieces. I want each class or module to have a specific responsibility, 
and I want my tests to confirm that each part works before combining it with the rest of the system.

Overall, this project helped me understand that software design and testing are connected. Good design makes testing easier, and good testing helps confirm that the design actually meets the requirements.
